title: East college football roundup: No. 25 Pittsburgh holds off Syracuse
text:
East college football roundup: No. 25 Pittsburgh holds off Syracuse October 25, 2015 Last updated: Sunday, October 25, 2015, 1:21 AM STAFF AND NEWS SERVICE REPORTS | The Record Print 
Chris Blewitt kicked a 25-yard field goal as time expired to lift No. 25 Pittsburgh over Syracuse, 23-20, on Saturday at Syracuse, N.Y. 
The Panthers (6-1, 4-0 ACC) now have won four of five on the road, with their only loss at Iowa on a 57-yard field goal on the final play of the game. 
The Orange (3-4, 1-2 ACC) have lost four straight. 
Qadree Ollison ran for 98 yards and two touchdowns for the Panthers. 
With the score tied at 20 and time winding down, Pitt coach Pat Narduzzi called for a fake punt on fourth down near midfield. Punter Ryan Winslow hit Matt Galambos for 12 yards and a first down. 
LOUISVILLE 17, BOSTON COLLEGE 14 (at Louisville, Ky.) — Lamar Jackson ran for a short touchdown and passed for 230 yards, and the Cardinals’ defense made a big stand late. 
The Eagles (3-5, 0-5 Atlantic Coast Conference) had a final chance after recovering a fumble at midfield with 2:18 remaining, but they turned it over on downs when Troy Flutie was sacked for a 4-yard loss. The play capped a dominant defensive effort for Louisville (3-4, 2-2 Atlantic Coast Conference), which recorded eight sacks, held BC to minus-14 yards rushing and just 79 overall. 
Boston College forced four turnovers, including a 12-yard touchdown return of a blocked punt by Montclair’s Elijah Robinson. 
CINCINNATI 37, CONNECTICUT 13 (at Cincinnati) — Gunner Kiel made his first start in a month, threw two touchdown passes and ran for a third as the Bearcats (4-3, 1-2 American) topped the Huskies (3-5, 1-3), who came in with the second-best scoring defense in the conference at 20 points per game. 
HARVARD 42, PRINCETON 7 (at Cambridge, Mass.) — Scott Hosch threw for a career-high 437 yards and two touchdowns, and ran for another score as the Crimson (6-0, 3-0 Ivy League) romped. 
Chad Kanoff threw for 203 yards with one interception for the Tigers (4-2, 1-2). 
DARTMOUTH 13, COLUMBIA 9 (at Hanover, N.H.) — Dalyn Williams threw for 235 yards and a touchdown, and the Big Green (6-0, 3-0) overcame a penalty-filled performance. The Lions (1-5, 0-3 Ivy), losers of 26 of their last 27 games, fell to Dartmouth for the seventh consecutive time. 
COASTAL CAROLINA 23, MONMOUTH 20 (at West Long Branch) — Ryan Granger kicked a 30-yard field goal to end the game and give the Chanticleers (7-0, 2-0 Big South) a victory. 
Lavon Chaney ran for 196 yards with two touchdowns, and caught a touchdown pass to lead the Hawks (3-5, 1-2). 
FORDHAM 59, LEHIGH 42 (at New York) — Chase Edmonds had 31 carries, a Patriot League-record 347 yards and three touchdowns as the Rams (7-1, 3-0 Patriot League) held off the Mountain Hawks (3-4, 1-1). 
THE COLLEGE OF NEW JERSEY 23, MONTCLAIR STATE 20 (at Ewing) — Ryan Davies was 13 of 25 passing for 181 yards and two touchdowns, but the Red Hawks (3-4, 3-3 NJAC) had their three-game winning streak snapped against the Lions (1-5, 1-4). 
WILLIAM PATERSON 31, SOUTHERN VIRGINIA 27 (at Wayne) — Anthony DiMarsico had 242 yards and two touchdowns on 16 for 22 passing to lift the Pioneers (2-5, 1-5).
